MainClaim.text: "Spenser's recovery of place in The Faerie Queene

Claim1.text: "Spenser's celebration of Courtesy as a virtue involves an appreciation of social values as well as a commitment to transcendent notions of Good."

Claim2.text: "The difference between Spenser's conceptions of nature can be understood in terms of the tension that governs The Faerie Queene as a whole."

Claim3.text: "The idea that virtue can be institutional as well as basic to human communities underlines Spenser's epic narrative as a recovery of place which happens in language and ultimately concerns the movement of the soul toward imaginative fulfillment."

Claim4.text: "The recovery of place involves a slow spiritual awakening that embraces the lowest levels of erotic awareness as well as the highest reaches of 'ideal' experience."

Claim5.text: "The recovery of place becomes a sublime metaphor whose deeper meaning is corroborated by tradition and phenomenology alike."

Claim6.text: "The concept of imaginative fulfillment can be related to a broad range of human activities."
